00:00:32.730 --> 00:00:34.630
I should switch colors.

00:00:34.630 --> 00:00:38.660
So what's the antiderivative of
x y squared with respect to x?

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:44.000
Well it's just x
squared over 2.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:46.080
And then I have the y
squared-- that's just a

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:48.900
constant-- all over 2.

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:55.890
And I'm going to evaluate that
from x is equal to 1 to x is

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.660
equal to the square root of y,
which you might be daunted by.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:00.930
But you'll see that it's
actually not that bad

00:01:00.930 --> 00:01:01.630
once you evaluate them.

00:01:01.630 --> 00:01:03.540
And then let me draw the
outside of the integral.

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:06.620
This is y is equal to
0 to y is equal 1.

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:08.830
dy.

00:01:08.830 --> 00:01:11.640
Now, if x is equal to 1
this expression becomes

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:13.400
y squared over 2.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:14.470
Right?

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:19.030
y squared over 2, minus-- now
if x is equal to square root

00:01:19.030 --> 00:01:21.320
of y, what does this
expression become?

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:25.120
If x is equal to the
square root of y, then

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:27.250
x squared is just y.

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:30.870
And then y times y squared
is y to the third.

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:31.180
Right?

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:36.210
So it's y to the third over 3.

00:01:36.210 --> 00:01:36.830
Fair enough.

00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:40.870
And now I take the integral
with respect to y.

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:45.520
So now I sum up all of these
rectangles in the y direction.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:46.420
0, 1.

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:47.620
This is with respect to y.

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:48.910
And that's cool, right?

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:52.820
Because when you take the first
integral with respect to x you

00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:55.030
end up with a function of y
anyway, so you might as well

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:57.120
have your bounds as
functions of y's.

00:01:57.120 --> 00:01:59.510
It really doesn't make
it any more difficult.

00:01:59.510 --> 00:02:00.850
But anyway, back
to the problem.

00:02:00.850 --> 00:02:07.440
What is the antiderivative
of y squared over 2 minus

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:11.380
y to the third over 3?

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:15.430
Well the antiderivative of y
squared-- and you have to

00:02:15.430 --> 00:02:18.130
divide by 3, so it's
y cubed over 6.

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:23.670
Minus y to the fourth--
you have to divide by 4.

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:28.480
Minus y to the fourth over--
did I mess up some place?

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:32.385
No, I think this is correct.
y to the fourth over 12.

